column1:  We have observed multiple source address are trying to do ""HTTP Parser Attack"" on the multiple destination address on port 80 and 443.
HTTP parser attacks attempt to execute malicious code, extract information, or enact Denial of Service by targeting the HTTP parser directly.
 We have observed the WAF action is alerted, but multiple connections response code is 200.
 Attacker is trying to do POST and GET method
 As per the user Agents, we have observed Zgraber scanning, Python scripts, Censys scans and Gather Analyze Provide..ETC multiple tools are used to scan our network.
 As per the URL pattern, the attacker trying to fetch the admin Hash ""mstshash=administrator""
 So many scripts are using path traversal.
1. Please run vulnerability scan on the destination web applications and fix all the vulnerability.
2. Please block the signature ""HTTP Parser Attack"" in WAF.
3. Please block the Source address in the perimeter level.
4. Please block the User Agents in Proxy.

When using project management application in ServiceNow, users are getting ""Permission Denied"" error. A fix was developed in DEV. Can you please run it through SDLC and move the fix (update set: KG - Project Planning Console Indent Error Fix) to Production? More details are below.

Planning console is part of project workspace that project managers use to establish a project plan. One of the features in the console is the ability to indent/unindent the project tasks, similar to how it's done in Microsoft Project software, to move the tasks in the plan.
However, in c/MT instance, when project managers are trying to use the feature, they are getting 'Permission Denied"" error.

Indenting/Unindenting the tasks will update the parent field on project task with the relevant task number. However, this field is made ""Read Only"" in c/MT environment for a reason that I don't know. It means that the users can't build child/parent relationships using ""Parent"" field for any type of tasks.
An override has been added for ""Parent"" field on pm_project_task field to make it read/write. It enables the users to move the project tasks under different parent tasks.

column1: INCB8023961,2022-01-18 02:12:41,CU,"  RCA - Azure Resource Manager - Management Groups
The activity log alert Alert about Planned Maintenance and Service Issues was triggered by a service issue for the Azure subscription Microsoft Azure.

Summary of Impact: Between 22:00 UTC on 16 Dec 2021 and 10:15 UTC on 17 Dec 2021, customers using Management Groups may have experienced issues with permissions not being inherited by subscriptions from their associated Management Groups. This may have resulted in subscriptions not being listed correctly when querying Azure Resource Manager, the subscriptions themselves would not have been impacted.

Root Cause: A hotfix for a previous issue containing some performance updates for the Inherited Subscriptions API was rolled out. These performance updates unknowingly caused some issues with permissions not being propagated from Management Groups to subscriptions, and this caused the experience for some customers of subscriptions not being listed when querying Azure Resource Manager. This impact was only detected when the hotfix rolled progressed to a larger region with more traffic.
Mitigation: We rolled back the hotfix, which mitigated the issue.

Next Steps: We apologize for the impact to affected customers. We are continuously taking steps to improve the Microsoft Azure Platform and our processes to help ensure such incidents do not occur in the future. In this case, this includes (but is not limited to):
Improve monitoring to help alert to these issues earlier and allow transparency for each scenario
Improve testing - Create more scenarios for testing before rollout
Improve rollouts - Investigate the possibility of including one large region in earlier stages of rollout as this issue was not detected until rolled out to a larger region

INCB8145070,2022-02-08 17:59:20,CU,"  RCA - Log Analytics/Azure Sentinel – East US
The activity log alert Alert about Planned Maintenance and Service Issues was triggered by a service issue for the Azure subscription Microsoft Azure.

Summary of Impact: Between 07:30 UTC and 12:30 UTC on 15 Jan 2022, you were identified as a customer using Log Analytics and/or Azure Sentinel in East US who may have experienced ingestion latency, delayed or misfired alerts, and failures when performing service management operations – such as create, read, update, and delete - in the Log Analytics control plane APIs for resources hosted in the region.

Root Cause: One component of Log Analytics required its storage keys rotated, as part of routine periodic maintenance. However, in this instance, the key rotation did not complete successfully, resulting in Authentication errors. We subsequently determined the underlying cause of this to be an incorrect execution of the required update process.
Mitigation: We applied a new storage key and rebooted impacted instances, which mitigated the issue.

Next Steps: We apologize for the impact to affected customers. We are continuously taking steps to improve the Microsoft Azure Platform and our processes to help ensure such incidents do not occur in the future. In this case, this includes (but is not limited to):
Update process and documentation for rotating storage keys for this component.
Review of monitoring and alerting to ensure engineers are engaged at the earliest instance for issues similar to this

INCB8151202,2022-02-10 00:15:21,CU,"  RCA - Log Analytics/Azure Sentinel - Issues with Data Ingestion Latency and missed alerts
The activity log alert Alert about Planned Maintenance and Service Issues was triggered by a service issue for the Azure subscription Microsoft Azure.

Summary of Impact: Between 14:00 UTC and 15:15 UTC on 25 Jan 2022, customers using Azure Log Analytics or Azure Sentinel in East US region may have experienced issues with data ingestion latency, data gaps and delayed or missed alerts for resources hosted in the region.

Root Cause: A Virtual Machine (VM) node in one of the backend scale units in this region went into an unhealthy state after a service restart. During the service restart, there was an increase in outbound traffic from that VM which caused the service to enter into an unhealthy state due to the volume of outbound calls. This prevented successful processing of incoming requests to this node.
Mitigation: The unhealthy VM node was restarted to get back to an overall healthy state which mitigated the issue.

Next Steps: We apologize for the impact to affected customers. We are continuously taking steps to improve the Microsoft Azure Platform and our processes to help ensure such incidents do not occur in the future. In this case, this includes (but is not limited to):
Identify and update the code in the ingestion service to help prevent node instances from going into an unhealthy state on a service restart.

column1: INCB8245285,2022-03-08 06:11:10,CU,"  RCA - Azure Log Analytics - East US
The activity log alert Alert about Planned Maintenance and Service Issues was triggered by a service issue for the Azure subscription Microsoft Azure.

Summary of Impact: Between 16:16 UTC on 16 Feb 2022 and 06:35 UTC on 17 Feb 2022, you were identified as a customer using Azure Log Analytics/Azure Monitor Search Alert in East US who may have experienced data latency, data gaps and missed or delayed alert.

Root Cause: Data flowing from a pipeline for scale units in East US was impacted when ingestion service instances that had been inadvertently running a legacy configuration, were affected by a configuration update. These service instances were unable to process incoming requests and caused latency for a subset of data types for Azure Log Analytics and Log queries.
Mitigation: We initially experienced issues reverting the configuration update, and redeployed the service in order to mitigate the issue.

Next Step: We apologize for the impact to affected customers. We are continuously taking steps to improve the Microsoft Azure Platform and our processes to help ensure such incidents do not occur in the future. In this case, this includes (but is not limited to):
Further investigation on improving the time to mitigate this issue by addressing issues with reverting the configuration update
Investigate issues in the deployment pipeline which led to the service instances being on the legacy configuration
Provide Feedback: Please help us improve the Azure customer communications experience by taking our survey: https://aka.ms/AzurePIRSurvey [https://aka.ms/AzurePIRSurvey]
